  • Write one function that does steps 1 & 2 above. Give an optional argument (that is it has a default value) that allows the user to specify the name of the column representing the value (enrollment for these data sets).
selectVar <- function(input) {
  data2 <- input %>% 
  rename(area_name = Area_name) %>% 
  select(area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D"))
  selected_data <- data2 %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = 3:12, names_to = "EDU", values_to = "enrollment_value")
  
  return(selected_data)
}

selected_data <- selectVar(data1)
  • Write another function that takes in the output of step 2 and does step 3 above.
numVar <- function(input) {
  dates <- as.Date(substr(input$EDU, start = 8, stop = 9), "%y")
  yr <- as.numeric(format(dates, "%Y"))
  num_data <- input %>% mutate(year = yr)
  return(num_data)
}

num_data <- numVar(selected_data)
  • Write a function to do step 5
selectCounty <- function(input) {
  county_level <- input %>% 
    mutate(state = substr(input$area_name,
                          nchar(input$area_name)-1,
                          nchar(input$area_name)))
  return(county_level)
}

county_level <- selectCounty(num_data)
  • Write a function to do step 6

  • Write another function that takes in the output from step 3 and creates the two tibbles in step 4, calls the above two functions (to perform steps 5 and 6), and returns two final tibbles.
createTwoData <- function(input) {
  county_num <- grep(pattern = ", \\w\\w", input$area_name)
  noncounty_data <- input %>% filter(!(row_number() %in% county_num))
  county_data <- input %>% filter((row_number() %in% county_num))
  
  county_level <- selectCounty(county_data)
  noncounty_level <- selectNonCounty(noncounty_data)
  class(county_data) <- c("county", class(county_data))
  class(noncounty_data) <- c("state", class(noncounty_data))
  
  return(list(county_level, noncounty_level))
}

two_tibble <- createTwoData(num_data)
county_level <- two_tibble[1]
#county_level
noncounty_level <- two_tibble[2]
#noncounty_level

Now last thing, put it all into one function call! This is called creating a wrapper function. Create a function that takes in the URL of a .csv file in this format and the optional argument for the variable name, calls the functions you wrote above, and then returns the two tibbles.

my_wrapper <- function(url, default_var_name = "default of some kind") { 
  #a <- read_csv_code(...)
  readdata <- read_csv(url)
  #b <- function_for_step_1_2(a, ...)
  selectdata <- selectVar(readdata)
  #c <- function_for_step_3(b, ...)
  changeyear <- numVar(selectdata)
  #d <- function_for_steps4_5_6(c, ...) (where this function calls the other functions mentioned
  twoTibbles <- createTwoData(changeyear)
  #return final result
  return(twoTibbles)
}

result <- my_wrapper("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01b.csv")
county_data <- result[1]
noncounty_data <- result[2]

Call It and Combine Your Data

Call the function you made two times to read in and parse the two .csv files mentioned so far. Be sure to call the new value column the same in both function calls.

result_a <- my_wrapper("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv")
result_b <- my_wrapper("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01b.csv")

Write a small function that takes in the results of two calls to your wrapper function and combines the tibbles appropriately (that is the two county level data sets get combined and the two non-county level data sets get combined). This can easily be done using dplyr::bind_rows().

combineTwoData <- function(input_a, input_b) {
  county_data_a <- input_a[1]
  noncounty_data_a <- input_a[2]
  county_data_b <- input_b[1]
  noncounty_data_b <- input_b[2]
  county_combined <- dplyr::bind_rows(county_data_a, county_data_b)
  noncounty_combined <- dplyr::bind_rows(noncounty_data_a, noncounty_data_b)
  return(list(county_combined, noncounty_combined))
}

combined <- combineTwoData(result_a, result_b)
twoCounty <- combined[1]
twoNonCounty <- combined[2]

Write a Generic Function for Summarizing

First steps

For the state plotting method, let’s write a function that plots the mean value of the statistic (enrollment for this data set) across the years for each Division. That is, on the x-axis we want the numeric year value, on the y-axis we want the mean of the statistic for each Division and numeric year. Also, we want to remove observations at the ERROR setting of Division. Let me help you out since we haven’t covered plotting (make sure you have loaded the tidyverse).

plot.state <- function(input) {
  new_input <- do.call(rbind.data.frame, input)
  new_data <- new_input %>% 
    select(division, year, enrollment_value) %>%
    group_by(division, year) %>% 
    filter(division != "ERROR") %>%
    summarize(mean_of_stats = mean(enrollment_value))
  ggplot(new_data, aes(x = year, y = mean_of_stats, color = division)) + 
    geom_line()
}

Test out this function by running plot(_class_state_df_here_, var_name = ...). (This doesn’t need to go into the report here, just make sure it is working!)

plot.state(twoNonCounty)

For the class county we’ll do a similar plotting function but with more flexibility. This function should allow the user to: - specify the state of interest, giving a default value if not specified - determine whether the ‘top’ or ‘bottom’ most counties should be looked at with a default for ‘top’ - instruct how many of the ‘top’ or ‘bottom’ will be investigated with a default value of 5

Within your plot function you should:

  • filter the data to only include data from the state specified
  • find the overall mean of the statistic (use get(var_name) here as well) for each Area_name and sort those values from largest to smallest if ‘top’ is specified or smallest to largest if ‘bottom’ is specified
  • obtain the top or bottom x number of Area_names from the previous step where x is given by the user or the default
  • filter the data for this state to only include the Area_name’s from the previous part (this is the data we’ll use to plot)
  • use the plot code here to create a line plot:
plot.county <- function(input, state_name="NC", size = 5) {
  new_input <- do.call(rbind.data.frame, input)
  sort_data <- new_input %>%
    filter(state == state_name) %>%
    group_by(area_name) %>%
    summarize(mean_of_stats = mean(enrollment_value)) %>%
    top_n(size, mean_of_stats)

  new_data <- new_input %>%
    filter(area_name %in% sort_data$area_name)
  ggplot(new_data, aes(x = year, y = enrollment_value, color = area_name)) + 
    geom_line()
}

Notice we aren’t plotting the means here, the actual statistic’s value. Test out this function by running plot(_class_county_df_here_). Run it a few more times specifying different input arguments.

plot.county(twoCounty, state_name = "ID", size = 5)
